WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.452 --> 00:00:04.214
CASTLE: <i>There are
two kinds of folks</i>

2
00:00:04.238 --> 00:00:05.548
<i>who sit around thinking
about how to kill people:</i>

3
00:00:05.572 --> 00:00:06.733
<i>psychopaths and mystery writers.</i>

4
00:00:06.757 --> 00:00:08.318
<i>I'm the kind that pays better.
Who am I?</i>

5
00:00:08.342 --> 00:00:09.419
I'm Rick Castle.

6
00:00:09.443 --> 00:00:10.642
Castle. Castle.

7
00:00:10.710 --> 00:00:12.672
I really am
ruggedly handsome.
aren't I?

8
00:00:12.696 --> 00:00:15.030
<i>Every writer needs inspiration
and I found mine.</i>

9
00:00:15.099 --> 00:00:16.099
Detective Kate Beckett.

10
00:00:16.166 --> 00:00:17.315
Beckett. Beckett.

11
00:00:17.384 --> 00:00:19.029
"Nikki Heat"?
The character
he's basing on you.

12
00:00:19.053 --> 00:00:20.697
<i>And thanks to my friendship
with the mayor.</i>

13
00:00:20.721 --> 00:00:21.920
<i>I get to be on her case.</i>

14
00:00:21.989 --> 00:00:23.555
I'd be happy
to let you spank me.

15
00:00:23.607 --> 00:00:25.724
<i>And together we catch killers.</i>

16
00:00:25.793 --> 00:00:27.053
We make a pretty good team.
you know.

17
00:00:27.077 --> 00:00:28.843
Like Starsky and Hutch.
Turner and Hooch.

18
00:00:28.912 --> 00:00:31.312
You do remind me
a little of Hooch.

19
00:00:41.041 --> 00:00:43.442
PHOTOGRAPHER: Sexy. sexy.

20
00:00:43.511 --> 00:00:46.789
Ladies. I love it.
I love it. I love it.
Sexy. Sexy's not a crime.

21
00:00:46.813 --> 00:00:49.109
FEMALE REPORTER:
What's so special
about world-famous

22
00:00:49.133 --> 00:00:51.561
mystery novelist Richard Castle?

23
00:00:51.585 --> 00:00:53.163
He's rich. he's handsome.

24
00:00:53.187 --> 00:00:55.854
and he's basing his next
best seller on you.

25
00:00:55.923 --> 00:00:58.752
Tell me. Detective Beckett.
what's it like being
the inspiration

26
00:00:58.776 --> 00:01:02.727
for thrill-master
Richard Castle's
new character. Nikki Heat?

27
00:01:02.796 --> 00:01:04.496
On behalf of the NYPD.

28
00:01:04.565 --> 00:01:09.033
it has been a pleasure to
offer Mr. Castle insight
into the profession.

29
00:01:09.103 --> 00:01:10.680
Given all his
best sellers.
it's obvious

30
00:01:10.704 --> 00:01:13.082
Mr. Castle
has tremendous insight
into the criminal mind.

31
00:01:13.106 --> 00:01:14.917
I'm told in many occasions.

32
00:01:14.941 --> 00:01:18.894
his participation was
essential to solving
your toughest cases.

33
00:01:18.963 --> 00:01:22.264
Really? You were
told that? By who?

34
00:01:22.332 --> 00:01:23.960
By Castle.
PHOTOGRAPHER: Sexy.

35
00:01:23.984 --> 00:01:26.129
Try unbuttoning his shirt.
Just. just the first one
right there.

36
00:01:26.153 --> 00:01:27.631
Could you excuse me
for a moment?

37
00:01:27.655 --> 00:01:29.538
PHOTOGRAPHER:
Yeah. I love it.

38
00:01:29.606 --> 00:01:32.657
Sir. could I talk
to you in private
for a moment. please?

39
00:01:32.726 --> 00:01:33.920
Beckett. I have a couple...

40
00:01:33.944 --> 00:01:35.104
Now.

41
00:01:37.130 --> 00:01:39.030
We had a deal. Beckett.

42
00:01:41.335 --> 00:01:43.295
The deal is off.
What's the problem?

43
00:01:43.320 --> 00:01:46.266
Not only does he have
the bachelor-party
cop twins out there

44
00:01:46.290 --> 00:01:50.058
using him as a stripper pole
while I make nicey-nice
with the press.

45
00:01:50.127 --> 00:01:51.771
but do you know
what he said?
No.

46
00:01:51.795 --> 00:01:54.915
He said that he has been
instrumental in helping us
solve crimes.

47
00:01:54.948 --> 00:01:56.631
Well. hasn't he?

48
00:01:56.700 --> 00:01:57.949
That's not the point.

49
00:01:58.018 --> 00:02:01.186
Do you know how
hard it is for NYPD
to get good press?

50
00:02:01.255 --> 00:02:03.538
I mean. in a magazine
that people actually read?

51
00:02:03.607 --> 00:02:05.685
This article is
very important
to the mayor.

52
00:02:05.709 --> 00:02:10.495
therefore we are
going to cooperate.
Do I make myself clear?

53
00:02:13.166 --> 00:02:14.850
Okay. Fine.

54
00:02:16.203 --> 00:02:19.037
RYAN: It was nice
to meet you.

55
00:02:19.105 --> 00:02:21.050
We should have
photo shoots here
more often.

56
00:02:21.074 --> 00:02:23.434
Hey. Beckett.
how come you don't wear
a uniform like that?

57
00:02:23.476 --> 00:02:26.211
Because I don't wanna
get paid in singles.

58
00:02:26.280 --> 00:02:27.328
Hey.

59
00:02:28.865 --> 00:02:31.628
RYAN: Oh. hey.
don't we have
that thing?

60
00:02:31.652 --> 00:02:32.684
No.

61
00:02:32.753 --> 00:02:34.913
Yeah. You know.
the thing with the guy.

62
00:02:34.972 --> 00:02:36.605
Oh. yeah.
The thing with the guy.

63
00:02:36.673 --> 00:02:39.040
Yeah. excuse us.

64
00:02:39.109 --> 00:02:43.211
I just wanted you to know
I had nothing to do with this.

65
00:02:43.280 --> 00:02:44.746
I mean. it was the magazine.

66
00:02:44.815 --> 00:02:48.133
Well. the mayor thought
it would be good press.

67
00:02:48.201 --> 00:02:50.113
You don't have to
explain yourself.
Really?

68
00:02:50.137 --> 00:02:53.238
Really. See?
I don't care anymore.

69
00:02:53.306 --> 00:02:57.709
Now. if you'll excuse me.
I have an interview
to get back to.

70
00:02:57.778 --> 00:02:59.628
What did I do that was so wrong?

71
00:02:59.696 --> 00:03:01.596
The one thing
I asked you not to do.

72
00:03:01.665 --> 00:03:03.476
Okay. so you asked me
not to look into your
mother's murder.

73
00:03:03.500 --> 00:03:04.599
But look at what I found.

74
00:03:04.668 --> 00:03:06.312
It doesn't matter
what you found.

75
00:03:06.336 --> 00:03:08.314
I put that all
behind me
a long time ago.

76
00:03:08.338 --> 00:03:10.333
We can get back to
the interview now.

77
00:03:10.357 --> 00:03:12.903
Nope. you're gonna
have to reschedule.
We just caught a body.

78
00:03:12.927 --> 00:03:14.770
So sorry to step
out on you. Amy.

79
00:03:14.794 --> 00:03:16.644
Oh! Are you kidding?
It's perfect.

80
00:03:16.713 --> 00:03:19.448
A chance to see Castle
in action. Our readers'll
love it.

81
00:03:19.516 --> 00:03:21.043
Well. we wouldn't want to
disappoint your readers.

82
00:03:21.067 --> 00:03:22.217
now. would we. Detective?

83
00:03:27.390 --> 00:03:29.024
(SIRENS WAILING)

84
00:03:34.047 --> 00:03:35.792
Hey. can we talk
about this. please?

85
00:03:35.816 --> 00:03:37.849
There's nothing to talk about.

86
00:03:37.918 --> 00:03:39.296
Well. just at least
let me know what I can
do to make it up to you.

87
00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:40.719
You could leave me alone.

88
00:03:40.787 --> 00:03:43.066
Yes. well. I tried that.
and it didn't work.

89
00:03:43.090 --> 00:03:45.450
Hey. I could buy you a pony!

90
00:03:46.293 --> 00:03:48.727
Focus. Castle.
Crime scene. okay?

91
00:03:55.402 --> 00:03:57.035
It's raining men.

92
00:03:58.038 --> 00:04:00.054
Castle. what are you doing here?

93
00:04:00.123 --> 00:04:01.918
Don't worry.
We're still mad at him.

94
00:04:01.942 --> 00:04:04.625
A guy in a tree.
Mom and Dad bickering.
Seems like old times.

95
00:04:04.694 --> 00:04:05.821
How's it going up there?

96
00:04:05.845 --> 00:04:07.779
I got tree branches
poking my boobs

97
00:04:07.847 --> 00:04:09.714
and spotlights
shining up my booty.

98
00:04:09.783 --> 00:04:12.717
Could be worse.
You could be
wearing a skirt.

99
00:04:13.987 --> 00:04:16.187
When I come down.
I'm gonna smack you.

100
00:04:16.256 --> 00:04:17.484
I'll be looking forward to that.

101
00:04:17.508 --> 00:04:18.639
Here.

102
00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:21.993
Vic's a white male. late 30s.

103
00:04:22.061 --> 00:04:23.779
Judging from
the cracked branches.

104
00:04:23.847 --> 00:04:26.831
I'm guessing he did
a Superman off the top
of that building.

105
00:04:26.900 --> 00:04:28.366
ESPOSITO: Vic's name
is John Allen.

106
00:04:28.418 --> 00:04:30.485
ID has him on
the Upper West Side.

107
00:04:30.553 --> 00:04:31.898
Business card has him
in insurance.

108
00:04:31.922 --> 00:04:32.988
Hmm.

109
00:04:33.056 --> 00:04:34.266
Is it a suicide?

110
00:04:34.290 --> 00:04:36.408
BOTH: It's not a suicide.

111
00:04:36.477 --> 00:04:38.143
How do you know?

112
00:04:38.945 --> 00:04:40.712
The building is too short.

113
00:04:40.780 --> 00:04:42.875
He'd wanna kill himself.
not cripple himself.

114
00:04:42.899 --> 00:04:45.900
If you wanna die.
you're gonna aim for
concrete. not a tree.

115
00:04:45.969 --> 00:04:47.753
Judging from
the angle of descent.

116
00:04:47.821 --> 00:04:50.088
I'd say that guy
was thrown off
the building.

117
00:04:50.157 --> 00:04:53.291
Since it clearly
wasn't a suicide.
how did he die?

118
00:04:53.360 --> 00:04:54.976
There are signs
of strangulation.

119
00:04:55.045 --> 00:04:57.011
It looks like his
windpipe was crushed.

120
00:04:57.080 --> 00:04:58.640
Any ligature marks?
LANIE: Nope.

121
00:04:58.682 --> 00:05:00.749
Ligature refers to
anything that ties
or binds.

122
00:05:00.834 --> 00:05:02.450
like a rope or a belt.

123
00:05:02.518 --> 00:05:04.597
The lack of any marks
suggest he was
strangled by hand.

124
00:05:04.621 --> 00:05:06.066
Wow. you really know your stuff.

125
00:05:06.090 --> 00:05:07.650
No wonder they like
having you around.

126
00:05:07.674 --> 00:05:10.441
BECKETT: You know what?
He's such an incredible
resource.

127
00:05:10.511 --> 00:05:13.528
it seems like a shame
to waste his talents
here in the field.

128
00:05:13.596 --> 00:05:15.491
Would you mind going back
to the morgue with Dr. Parish

129
00:05:15.515 --> 00:05:17.860
to see what else
you can find out
about the vic?

130
00:05:17.884 --> 00:05:19.812
Don't you think I'd
be of more use here
at the crime scene?

131
00:05:19.836 --> 00:05:22.047
Oh. no. We're just
gonna knock on doors

132
00:05:22.071 --> 00:05:23.750
and see what we
else can stir up.

133
00:05:23.774 --> 00:05:25.685
You know. boring police stuff.

134
00:05:25.709 --> 00:05:28.694
Fine. But I was serious
about the pony.

135
00:05:28.762 --> 00:05:31.563
Come on. I'll show you
the morgue-mobile.

136
00:05:33.967 --> 00:05:35.178
Anything in the wallet?

137
00:05:35.202 --> 00:05:37.336
Nope.
Dry-cleaning ticket. ID.

138
00:05:37.404 --> 00:05:40.271
two credit cards.
Cash was missing. though.

139
00:05:41.658 --> 00:05:44.342
That's a long way
to go for a robbery.

140
00:05:48.131 --> 00:05:50.815
You mean we have to
ride with the body?

141
00:05:50.884 --> 00:05:52.445
You can take my seat up front.

142
00:05:52.469 --> 00:05:53.935
You sure?

143
00:05:54.003 --> 00:05:56.571
I'm used to hanging out
with stiffs.

144
00:06:07.084 --> 00:06:08.416
Hi.

145
00:06:08.484 --> 00:06:09.996
Uh-uh. You do not
get to say hi to me.

146
00:06:10.020 --> 00:06:11.630
I'm just doing my girl a favor.

147
00:06:11.654 --> 00:06:13.688
You. too. huh?

148
00:06:13.757 --> 00:06:15.423
Well. what did you expect?

149
00:06:15.492 --> 00:06:17.870
Beckett spent
the first three years
of being a cop

150
00:06:17.894 --> 00:06:19.438
trying to solve
her mother's murder.

151
00:06:19.462 --> 00:06:21.674
It took everything
that she had to
put it behind her.

152
00:06:21.698 --> 00:06:23.009
You couldn't respect that?

153
00:06:23.033 --> 00:06:25.177
What was I supposed to do?
Not tell her what I found?

154
00:06:25.201 --> 00:06:26.567
What you found?

155
00:06:26.636 --> 00:06:28.854
She didn't tell you. did she?

156
00:06:30.691 --> 00:06:33.257
Three people were killed
the same way her mother was.

157
00:06:33.326 --> 00:06:34.659
right about the same time.

158
00:06:34.728 --> 00:06:37.428
One of them was a former
law student of hers.

159
00:06:37.497 --> 00:06:39.363
Another one. a documents clerk.

160
00:06:39.432 --> 00:06:42.183
The third one.
a lawyer for
a non-profit.

161
00:06:42.252 --> 00:06:44.619
Wait. The ME at the time
didn't make the connection?

162
00:06:44.688 --> 00:06:46.482
If he did. he buried it.

163
00:06:46.506 --> 00:06:47.889
Did you talk to him?

164
00:06:47.958 --> 00:06:49.941
He died four years ago.

165
00:06:51.327 --> 00:06:54.045
So you see why
I had to tell her.

166
00:06:54.113 --> 00:06:55.814
What did she say?

167
00:06:57.517 --> 00:07:00.518
That we were done.
And then she just walked...

168
00:07:00.587 --> 00:07:01.953
(CRASHING)

169
00:07:06.343 --> 00:07:07.687
Don't move.
Don't move!

170
00:07:07.711 --> 00:07:08.843
Whoa!

171
00:07:10.580 --> 00:07:12.113
THUG 1: Get the body!

172
00:07:15.952 --> 00:07:20.938
Go! Don't move!
Come on. move! Go!

173
00:07:27.130 --> 00:07:29.931
Is it just me.
or was that really.
really weird?

174
00:07:37.758 --> 00:07:39.724
MONTGOMERY: Well?
He'll live.

175
00:07:40.493 --> 00:07:41.793
What. no brain damage?

176
00:07:41.862 --> 00:07:43.773
If he has some.
it happened way
before tonight

177
00:07:43.797 --> 00:07:45.680
and was probably self-inflicted.

178
00:07:45.749 --> 00:07:46.881
Good times.

179
00:07:46.950 --> 00:07:48.694
How's Lois Lane?
Who. reporter chick?

180
00:07:48.718 --> 00:07:50.646
Yeah. We took her statement
and we sent her home.

181
00:07:50.670 --> 00:07:53.521
We got an APB on the sedan.
CSUs are combing the rooftop.

182
00:07:53.589 --> 00:07:55.985
and we got unis looking
for surveillance footage
at the crash site.

183
00:07:56.009 --> 00:07:58.827
You know what I don't get is.
who would steal a dead body?

184
00:07:58.895 --> 00:08:01.730
Plenty of people.
Organ harvesters.

185
00:08:01.798 --> 00:08:04.432
cadaver-less med students.
Satanists.

186
00:08:04.500 --> 00:08:07.060
mad scientists
looking to create
their own monster.

187
00:08:07.104 --> 00:08:10.505
Or the guys who killed him
might have left some
evidence behind.

188
00:08:10.574 --> 00:08:16.211
Boring. How about a spy
having swallowed
a top-secret microchip

189
00:08:16.280 --> 00:08:18.947
that the enemy forces
murder him over

190
00:08:19.016 --> 00:08:21.496
before the CIA can
get a hold of him?

191
00:08:21.551 --> 00:08:23.229
As much as we all
appreciate your insightful

192
00:08:23.253 --> 00:08:25.053
and incredibly
believable theories.

193
00:08:25.122 --> 00:08:28.206
Ms. Cosmo is gone.
so I believe you can
go home now.

194
00:08:28.274 --> 00:08:31.459
Home? No. No. no. no.
This case just got good.

195
00:08:31.527 --> 00:08:34.229
And I'm a witness.

196
00:08:38.902 --> 00:08:41.280
All right.
I'll let you work
this one case with me

197
00:08:41.304 --> 00:08:43.549
if you promise
to leave me alone
when it's over

198
00:08:43.573 --> 00:08:46.074
and not to weasel
your way back in.

199
00:08:47.210 --> 00:08:50.578
Deal. But fair warning.
Detective.

200
00:08:50.647 --> 00:08:53.181
I will make you
change your mind.

201
00:08:53.250 --> 00:08:55.116
I won't.
You will.

202
00:08:55.185 --> 00:08:58.419
CASTLE: So what's
the next step?
Victim's family?

203
00:08:58.488 --> 00:09:00.988
I didn't think
she'd take him back.

204
00:09:01.891 --> 00:09:03.608
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

205
00:09:04.811 --> 00:09:06.845
Mrs. Allen?
Yes?

206
00:09:06.914 --> 00:09:09.246
It's about your husband.

207
00:09:09.315 --> 00:09:13.050
He was just right here.
just a couple of hours ago.

208
00:09:13.119 --> 00:09:14.885
And now he's dead.

209
00:09:18.225 --> 00:09:20.653
Do you know of any
reason why he'd be
in that part of town?

210
00:09:20.677 --> 00:09:26.765
No. His office is in Midtown.
It's nowhere near Ninth.

211
00:09:26.833 --> 00:09:28.867
What time did he leave
the apartment?

212
00:09:28.936 --> 00:09:30.902
Around 6:00.

213
00:09:30.971 --> 00:09:32.820
He'd just gotten back
from his trip

214
00:09:32.889 --> 00:09:36.958
and he said he
needed to catch up
on some paperwork.

215
00:09:37.027 --> 00:09:39.144
He said he'd only be gone
for a couple of hours.

216
00:09:39.212 --> 00:09:40.511
You said "a trip"?

217
00:09:40.580 --> 00:09:43.481
He was in Albuquerque
on a training seminar.

218
00:09:44.217 --> 00:09:46.251
It was just two nights.

219
00:09:46.320 --> 00:09:48.330
Did you notice anything
unusual recently?

220
00:09:48.354 --> 00:09:50.955
Any strange behavior?

221
00:09:51.023 --> 00:09:55.360
Well. he had to work late
a little more often
than usual.

222
00:09:55.428 --> 00:09:59.029
but. I mean.
in this economy.
who doesn't?

223
00:09:59.098 --> 00:10:01.966
He had to lay off
half his department
last year.

224
00:10:02.034 --> 00:10:05.253
And you're sure
he was working late?

225
00:10:05.321 --> 00:10:08.139
What are you saying?
That he was cheating?

226
00:10:11.178 --> 00:10:13.244
Every night.
he would walk
through that door.

227
00:10:13.313 --> 00:10:16.530
and the kids would just
race into his arms. okay?

228
00:10:17.367 --> 00:10:19.851
And now he's gone.

229
00:10:19.920 --> 00:10:22.854
So don't ask me
if he was really
working late.

230
00:10:22.923 --> 00:10:25.389
Tell me why he was killed.

231
00:10:25.458 --> 00:10:27.236
He didn't mean to imply...
What about phone calls?

232
00:10:27.260 --> 00:10:28.337
Maybe late at night?

233
00:10:28.361 --> 00:10:29.877
Castle.

234
00:10:29.963 --> 00:10:35.784
Yeah. Yeah.
One of the guys that
John fired. Max Haverstock.

235
00:10:35.852 --> 00:10:37.819
he would call him up
late at night

236
00:10:37.888 --> 00:10:40.755
and he would yell at him.
all sorts of things.

237
00:10:40.824 --> 00:10:43.892
I guess he was hurting.
he needed money.

238
00:10:43.960 --> 00:10:46.895
And I. I told John
that he should just
hang up on him.

239
00:10:46.963 --> 00:10:49.564
and John said no.
he couldn't do that.

240
00:10:49.632 --> 00:10:51.110
Did he ever give him money?

241
00:10:51.134 --> 00:10:53.334
My husband didn't
believe in handouts.

242
00:10:53.403 --> 00:10:56.254
He believed that a man
should make his way.

243
00:10:59.209 --> 00:11:02.610
Where is he?
I'd like to say goodbye.

244
00:11:07.834 --> 00:11:09.283
About that. um...

245
00:11:12.222 --> 00:11:13.854
That was awkward.

246
00:11:15.024 --> 00:11:16.891
It just. it doesn't
make any sense.

247
00:11:16.960 --> 00:11:18.737
The guy's got a stable.
middle-class life.

248
00:11:18.761 --> 00:11:20.929
Good job. good family.

249
00:11:20.997 --> 00:11:22.446
Maybe his friend Max
was jealous.

250
00:11:22.499 --> 00:11:25.867
Yeah. maybe enough to
kill him. but to steal
his body?

251
00:11:25.936 --> 00:11:30.371
Hey. Esposito. I need you
to look up a friend
of the vic. Max Haverstock.

252
00:11:32.575 --> 00:11:33.708
Yeah.

253
00:11:36.746 --> 00:11:39.113
Okay. find him and bring him in.

254
00:11:44.570 --> 00:11:46.838
Dad. Thank God you're home.
Are you okay?

255
00:11:46.906 --> 00:11:48.439
Yeah. I'm fine. Why?

256
00:11:48.508 --> 00:11:50.608
"Fine"? Masked gunmen.
body snatchers?

257
00:11:50.677 --> 00:11:52.171
I texted you. like.
a thousand times.

258
00:11:52.195 --> 00:11:56.164
I'm sorry. My phone
must have been off.
How did you know?

259
00:11:56.232 --> 00:11:57.765
Beckett called.

260
00:11:58.435 --> 00:11:59.667
Really?

261
00:11:59.736 --> 00:12:01.697
She just wanted
to let us know
you were all right.

262
00:12:01.721 --> 00:12:03.153
Mmm-hmm.

263
00:12:03.223 --> 00:12:05.256
So. has she forgiven you?

264
00:12:05.325 --> 00:12:07.909
Not exactly. Mother.
But I'm working on it.

265
00:12:07.978 --> 00:12:10.089
She has agreed to let me
help on the case.

266
00:12:10.113 --> 00:12:12.530
Well. that's a start. I suppose.

267
00:12:12.598 --> 00:12:16.417
It is more than a start.
It is an opportunity.

268
00:12:16.486 --> 00:12:18.330
She may have built
a wall between us.

269
00:12:18.354 --> 00:12:21.955
but I am going
to build a door
in that wall.

270
00:12:22.024 --> 00:12:24.759
or put up a ladder.
or dig a hole.

271
00:12:24.827 --> 00:12:26.293
You have a strategy?

272
00:12:26.362 --> 00:12:28.340
Be my usual charming self.

273
00:12:28.364 --> 00:12:31.332
Uh-huh.
What about plan B?

274
00:12:34.321 --> 00:12:36.048
So was it awful?
Were you scared?

275
00:12:36.072 --> 00:12:38.573
Me. scared?
No way. Come on.

276
00:12:38.642 --> 00:12:40.452
Now excuse me
while I change
my shorts.

277
00:12:40.476 --> 00:12:42.004
Dad.
No. I was scared.

278
00:12:42.028 --> 00:12:44.156
but all they were
after was the body.

279
00:12:44.180 --> 00:12:46.581
Why?
Why indeed?

280
00:12:46.649 --> 00:12:48.911
"Dad. where are you?"
"Dad. are you all right?"

281
00:12:48.935 --> 00:12:50.451
"Dad. call us right away."

282
00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:53.521
"Dad. can I go see <i>Fame</i>
with Owen on Friday?"

283
00:12:55.625 --> 00:12:57.436
Your concern is touching.

284
00:12:57.460 --> 00:12:59.422
Okay. that one
was after I knew
you were all right.

285
00:12:59.446 --> 00:13:00.872
Yeah. but I thought
we were gonna go see
that together.

286
00:13:00.896 --> 00:13:02.296
We were. and we still can.

287
00:13:02.365 --> 00:13:05.967
But he invited me
to go see it with him
next Friday.

288
00:13:06.036 --> 00:13:07.663
You'd rather go
with your boyfriend
than your dad?

289
00:13:07.687 --> 00:13:10.054
What is wrong with you?

290
00:13:10.122 --> 00:13:11.551
If you really want me
to go with you. I will.

291
00:13:11.575 --> 00:13:14.876
No. no. You tell Owen
he has won this round.

292
00:13:14.945 --> 00:13:17.356
but I got dibs on
<i>A Christmas Carol.</i>

293
00:13:17.380 --> 00:13:20.415
Thanks. Dad.
And I'm glad you weren't
killed by body snatchers.

294
00:13:20.483 --> 00:13:22.433
Me. too.

295
00:13:22.502 --> 00:13:24.669
They remade <i>Fame</i>
and <i>A Christmas Carol.</i>

296
00:13:24.738 --> 00:13:26.971
Has Hollywood totally
run out of ideas?

297
00:13:27.040 --> 00:13:30.319
Well. they just optioned
<i>Asteroids.</i> the videogame.
so my guess is yes.

298
00:13:30.343 --> 00:13:33.794
But Ryan Reynolds is
playing the wee triangle.
and he's good.

299
00:13:38.651 --> 00:13:40.580
Are you sure this is the guy?

300
00:13:40.604 --> 00:13:44.255
Maxwell Haverstock.
And he confirmed
he knew the vic.

301
00:13:44.323 --> 00:13:48.476
This guy couldn't throw
a wet sponge off the roof.
let alone a body.

302
00:13:53.582 --> 00:13:55.483
Mr. Haverstock?
Yes?

303
00:13:55.552 --> 00:13:57.195
Do you know why you're here?

304
00:13:57.219 --> 00:13:59.954
No. they just told me
I needed to come in.

305
00:14:00.022 --> 00:14:03.224
It's about John Allen.
He was murdered last night.

306
00:14:04.294 --> 00:14:05.893
That's terrible.

307
00:14:05.961 --> 00:14:07.328
You and he were friends.

308
00:14:07.397 --> 00:14:09.613
We had adjoining cubicles.

309
00:14:09.683 --> 00:14:11.966
When was the last time
you saw him?

310
00:14:12.034 --> 00:14:15.002
Not since D-Day.
That's what we called it.

311
00:14:15.071 --> 00:14:17.271
You know.
"D" for "downsizing."

312
00:14:17.357 --> 00:14:19.440
You were let go?
Yeah.

313
00:14:19.508 --> 00:14:21.436
I bet that made you
pretty angry.

314
00:14:21.460 --> 00:14:23.272
Yeah. Fifteen years
we worked there together.
you know.

315
00:14:23.296 --> 00:14:25.007
You'd think that
would mean something.

316
00:14:25.031 --> 00:14:27.414
You think that loyalty
would be worth something.

317
00:14:27.484 --> 00:14:30.151
You know what it's worth?
A kick in the teeth!

318
00:14:30.219 --> 00:14:31.613
Did you ever call
and tell John that?

319
00:14:31.637 --> 00:14:33.321
Yeah. all the time.

320
00:14:33.389 --> 00:14:35.468
Yeah. I told him
we didn't deserve to be
treated like that.

321
00:14:35.492 --> 00:14:38.209
But I promised him
one day the worm
would turn.

322
00:14:38.278 --> 00:14:40.594
'cause karma's
a nasty little bitch.

323
00:14:40.663 --> 00:14:42.983
Is that why you killed him?

324
00:14:43.833 --> 00:14:45.132
Who?

325
00:14:45.201 --> 00:14:46.700
John.

326
00:14:46.769 --> 00:14:48.836
Why would I wanna kill John?

327
00:14:48.904 --> 00:14:50.271
For firing you.

328
00:14:50.339 --> 00:14:54.542
He didn't fire me.
We were let go
together on D-Day.

329
00:14:54.610 --> 00:14:57.928
Fortunately. I was able
to find another job.

330
00:14:57.997 --> 00:15:00.597
He didn't have a job?

331
00:15:00.666 --> 00:15:03.768
I guess he doesn't have
to look for one anymore.

332
00:15:06.088 --> 00:15:08.956
Hey. yo. Beckett.
Story checks.

333
00:15:09.025 --> 00:15:12.171
John Allen was laid off
eight months ago
when the AIG crisis hit.

334
00:15:12.195 --> 00:15:13.794
What about Albuquerque?

335
00:15:13.863 --> 00:15:17.242
No record of a John Allen
coming back from any flight
in the Tri-State area.

336
00:15:17.266 --> 00:15:19.177
Well. makes you wonder
what else he lied
to his wife about.

337
00:15:19.201 --> 00:15:21.335
And how he paid
all of his bills.

338
00:15:21.404 --> 00:15:22.703
Beckett.

339
00:15:23.673 --> 00:15:25.706
All right. Thank you.

340
00:15:27.142 --> 00:15:29.710
They found his body. Again.

341
00:15:30.930 --> 00:15:32.596
(CAMERA CLICKING)

342
00:15:34.533 --> 00:15:36.067
What happened?

343
00:15:37.737 --> 00:15:40.588
Someone operated on him.

344
00:15:41.207 --> 00:15:42.773
Operated?

345
00:15:42.842 --> 00:15:45.320
They cut him open
and took all of
his organs out.

346
00:15:45.344 --> 00:15:47.662
(MEN EXCLAIMING IN DISGUST)

347
00:15:47.730 --> 00:15:50.047
Well. somebody hated his guts.

348
00:15:56.722 --> 00:15:58.333
LANIE: The guys
who did this
weren't surgeons.

349
00:15:58.357 --> 00:16:00.992
The cuts are sloppy.
Box cutters
and kitchen knives.

350
00:16:01.060 --> 00:16:02.760
Any idea what they
were looking for?

351
00:16:02.829 --> 00:16:05.141
I ran a tox screen
and found nothing
in the bloodstream.

352
00:16:05.165 --> 00:16:08.366
But in the body cavity itself
there were trace amounts of
powder cocaine.

353
00:16:08.418 --> 00:16:09.517
He was their drug mule.

354
00:16:09.586 --> 00:16:10.730
Guess they couldn't wait for him

355
00:16:10.754 --> 00:16:12.931
to pass the packets
the old-fashioned way.

356
00:16:12.955 --> 00:16:15.155
I don't buy it.

357
00:16:15.224 --> 00:16:17.558
How does a middle-aged
insurance actuary

358
00:16:17.627 --> 00:16:20.911
with no history
of substance abuse.
no criminal record.

359
00:16:20.980 --> 00:16:24.331
become a drug mule?
I mean. this was not
a bad guy.

360
00:16:24.400 --> 00:16:26.567
You don't just fill out
an ad on Craigslist.

361
00:16:26.636 --> 00:16:30.287
You gotta.
you gotta know people.
Bad people.

362
00:16:30.356 --> 00:16:33.774
As freaky as all this is.
let's not forget
it happened post mortem.

363
00:16:33.860 --> 00:16:36.560
The actual cause
of death is up here.

364
00:16:36.629 --> 00:16:41.098
Bruise pattern indicates
the assailant strangled him
with both hands.

365
00:16:41.167 --> 00:16:43.362
The bruising is
a little lighter
right there.

366
00:16:43.386 --> 00:16:44.697
What would account for that?

367
00:16:44.721 --> 00:16:46.904
Dislocated or
broken finger. maybe.

368
00:16:46.973 --> 00:16:51.359
Maybe he's fancy.
Strangle people with
his pinky sticking out.

369
00:16:53.480 --> 00:16:55.546
Like tea.

370
00:16:55.614 --> 00:16:58.532
Just got off
with Homeland Security.
Passport records indicate

371
00:16:58.601 --> 00:17:01.802
that John Allen was
coming back from Mexico.
not New Mexico.

372
00:17:01.871 --> 00:17:05.156
No criminal history.
healthy. white.
middle-class.

373
00:17:05.225 --> 00:17:07.603
They wouldn't have
looked at him twice
at customs.

374
00:17:07.627 --> 00:17:10.506
The guy had skills.
Why would he do
something so stupid?

375
00:17:10.530 --> 00:17:13.231
RYAN: Because he had to.

376
00:17:13.299 --> 00:17:15.861
I just went over
financials with the wife.
How bad?

377
00:17:15.885 --> 00:17:18.147
They've been living
on credit cards
the last six months.

378
00:17:18.171 --> 00:17:20.704
And she had no idea.
She thought everything
was fine.

379
00:17:20.773 --> 00:17:22.934
Well. if he wasn't
going to work every day.
where was he going?

380
00:17:22.958 --> 00:17:24.492
Applying for jobs.

381
00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:27.578
I found hundreds
of cover letters and
resumes on his computer.

382
00:17:27.647 --> 00:17:30.126
I don't understand.
Why didn't they just
sell the apartment?

383
00:17:30.150 --> 00:17:31.309
Wasn't worth the mortgage.

384
00:17:31.333 --> 00:17:32.399
That's harsh.

385
00:17:32.469 --> 00:17:33.768
Life insurance?

386
00:17:33.837 --> 00:17:35.703
Stopped making payments
four months ago.

387
00:17:35.772 --> 00:17:36.982
The guy was
basically worthless.
alive or dead.

388
00:17:37.006 --> 00:17:38.006
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

389
00:17:38.074 --> 00:17:40.207
Hey. Ryan here.

390
00:17:40.276 --> 00:17:43.277
You know. I get desperation.
I get needing the money.

391
00:17:43.346 --> 00:17:44.756
I even get being a drug mule.

392
00:17:44.780 --> 00:17:48.449
What I don't get is.
where did he get the job?

393
00:17:48.518 --> 00:17:51.018
Yeah. thanks. Bill.
That was CSU.

394
00:17:51.086 --> 00:17:52.464
Because our perps
were wearing gloves.

395
00:17:52.488 --> 00:17:53.999
the only prints
they grabbed off the car

396
00:17:54.023 --> 00:17:56.657
belonged to the owner
who reported it stolen
last night.

397
00:17:56.725 --> 00:17:58.845
Looks like we're not gonna
grab a break on this one.

398
00:17:58.878 --> 00:18:00.639
What about the glove
we found at the scene?

399
00:18:00.663 --> 00:18:02.713
Dusted it. too. Nothing.

400
00:18:02.781 --> 00:18:04.731
Well. did you dust inside?

401
00:18:04.800 --> 00:18:05.849
Inside?

402
00:18:05.918 --> 00:18:07.285
Yeah. inside the glove.

403
00:18:16.279 --> 00:18:19.180
You want me to
put on some music?

404
00:18:19.249 --> 00:18:21.832
Whenever they do this
sort of thing on <i>CSI.</i>

405
00:18:21.901 --> 00:18:24.986
they always do it to music
in poorly-lit rooms.

406
00:18:26.472 --> 00:18:29.190
It kind of reminds me of porn.

407
00:18:29.258 --> 00:18:30.791
Zip it. Castle.

408
00:18:34.847 --> 00:18:37.181
Ever consider becoming a mohel?

409
00:18:37.250 --> 00:18:39.867
Keep talking and
I'll practice on you.

410
00:18:50.546 --> 00:18:52.680
Got you. you son of a bitch.

411
00:18:58.571 --> 00:19:00.153
Boom! Got a hit.

412
00:19:01.841 --> 00:19:05.776
Luther Whitehead.
busted twice for
possession with intent.

413
00:19:05.845 --> 00:19:07.828
once on conspiracy.

414
00:19:07.897 --> 00:19:11.198
Pled out on all three.
Did a nickel upstate
for a gun charge

415
00:19:11.267 --> 00:19:14.168
and is currently on parole
for conspiracy to distribute.

416
00:19:14.237 --> 00:19:16.481
Something tells me
his parole's about
to be revoked.

417
00:19:16.505 --> 00:19:17.616
You got an address?

418
00:19:17.640 --> 00:19:18.823
Yeah.

419
00:19:18.891 --> 00:19:20.240
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

420
00:19:38.494 --> 00:19:39.693
LUTHER: Go!

421
00:19:43.782 --> 00:19:47.184
OFFICER 1:
Hold it right there!
OFFICER 2: Nobody move!

422
00:19:47.253 --> 00:19:49.570
OFFICER 3: Hands behind
your back. Hands!

423
00:20:01.800 --> 00:20:03.479
BECKETT: Counselor.
I have them dead to rights

424
00:20:03.503 --> 00:20:05.314
on weapons. possession. assault.

425
00:20:05.338 --> 00:20:07.649
desecration of a body.
and about a dozen
other things

426
00:20:07.673 --> 00:20:10.741
I haven't even begun
to think about yet.

427
00:20:10.809 --> 00:20:13.193
What is my incentive
to cut a deal?

428
00:20:13.262 --> 00:20:14.839
You don't have them
on the murder.

429
00:20:14.863 --> 00:20:16.097
Give me time.

430
00:20:16.165 --> 00:20:18.599
You don't need time.
because they didn't do it.

431
00:20:18.667 --> 00:20:22.186
Ten years concurrent
on all charges.
eligible in five.

432
00:20:22.255 --> 00:20:25.505
and they'll tell you
everything they know.

433
00:20:25.574 --> 00:20:27.569
He was coming to see you.

434
00:20:27.593 --> 00:20:31.228
At a flophouse on Ninth.
He was supposed to be
there by 7:00.

435
00:20:31.297 --> 00:20:35.032
But this guy. he got
three quarters of a mil worth
of our coke in his stomach.

436
00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:36.333
and he don't show.

437
00:20:36.402 --> 00:20:38.035
So what'd you do?

438
00:20:38.104 --> 00:20:41.205
We went to find him.
That's when we heard
the sirens. Lots of them.

439
00:20:41.273 --> 00:20:44.558
We go downstairs.
walk up the block
and guess what we see?

440
00:20:44.627 --> 00:20:46.494
A bunch of cops
staring at a tree.

441
00:20:46.562 --> 00:20:49.063
A frigging tree.
The dude was in a tree!

442
00:20:49.132 --> 00:20:50.748
So you waited?

443
00:20:50.816 --> 00:20:52.316
Only way to get the body back.

444
00:20:52.385 --> 00:20:54.952
I mean. we couldn't
get the packets
via the usual method.

445
00:20:55.020 --> 00:20:57.437
So you improvised.

446
00:20:57.507 --> 00:20:59.974
Doesn't matter.
He was already dead.

447
00:21:00.043 --> 00:21:01.654
So why'd he start muling?

448
00:21:01.678 --> 00:21:04.277
Same as anyone.
Desperation.

449
00:21:04.346 --> 00:21:07.081
It's just.
he doesn't seem the type.

450
00:21:07.149 --> 00:21:09.333
Anybody's the type.
you push them hard enough.

451
00:21:09.401 --> 00:21:10.634
I mean. the guy owed.

452
00:21:10.703 --> 00:21:14.355
He was fourth and long
with the clock running out.

453
00:21:14.423 --> 00:21:15.567
Who was he in to?

454
00:21:15.591 --> 00:21:17.608
Didn't say. but he was scared.

455
00:21:17.677 --> 00:21:20.811
You wanna know
who killed him.
you find out who he owed.

456
00:21:20.880 --> 00:21:22.541
No. no. no. no.
I'm gonna need more.

457
00:21:22.565 --> 00:21:24.309
I'm gonna need to know
who vouched.

458
00:21:24.333 --> 00:21:25.382
Vouched?

459
00:21:25.451 --> 00:21:27.901
For John Allen.
Our vic. your mule.

460
00:21:27.970 --> 00:21:30.771
Somebody brought him to you.
somebody you trusted.

461
00:21:30.840 --> 00:21:32.935
Or do you just do
business with every
desperate white boy

462
00:21:32.959 --> 00:21:35.087
with no history of
criminal activity?

463
00:21:35.111 --> 00:21:38.271
Hell. man!
How'd you know
he wasn't a cop?

464
00:21:41.116 --> 00:21:42.650
Got the printout.
Ron Bigby.

465
00:21:42.718 --> 00:21:44.351
He's a floor trader at Goldman.

466
00:21:44.420 --> 00:21:46.203
Vic's wife never heard the name.

467
00:21:46.272 --> 00:21:47.599
CASTLE: For a guy
who assesses risk
for a living.

468
00:21:47.623 --> 00:21:49.184
he sure does seem
to take a lot of it.

469
00:21:49.208 --> 00:21:51.419
Yeah. well. look
where it got him.
Pick him up.

470
00:21:51.443 --> 00:21:52.810
You got it.

471
00:21:54.881 --> 00:21:56.079
BECKETT: Castle.

472
00:21:59.401 --> 00:22:01.452
Dead?
Yeah.

473
00:22:01.521 --> 00:22:02.931
Dead?
BECKETT: Mr. Bigby.

474
00:22:02.955 --> 00:22:04.249
you can ask
as often as you like.

475
00:22:04.273 --> 00:22:06.554
The answer's not gonna change.

476
00:22:06.608 --> 00:22:10.043
That is a damn shame.
That is a damn. damn shame.

477
00:22:10.112 --> 00:22:12.646
I mean. do you know
who John Allen is? Huh?

478
00:22:12.714 --> 00:22:14.281
He's the new
Willy Loman. Okay?

479
00:22:14.350 --> 00:22:16.700
Everyman victim of
an apathetic world.

480
00:22:16.768 --> 00:22:18.880
God. I swear.
someone should
write a play.

481
00:22:18.904 --> 00:22:20.471
Hey. do you write plays?

482
00:22:20.540 --> 00:22:22.272
Unproduced.

483
00:22:22.341 --> 00:22:25.721
Mr. Bigby. it's come to our
attention that you recently
obtained employment

484
00:22:25.745 --> 00:22:28.145
for Mr. Allen
as a drug mule.

485
00:22:30.132 --> 00:22:31.264
You know about that?

486
00:22:31.333 --> 00:22:33.867
Yeah. And bad news. Ron.

487
00:22:33.936 --> 00:22:35.936
You're gonna have to
find a new dealer.

488
00:22:36.005 --> 00:22:38.534
What'd they tell you?
That you got him
an introduction.

489
00:22:38.558 --> 00:22:40.152
and that you vouched
for Mr. Allen.

490
00:22:40.176 --> 00:22:42.893
Okay. look. He came to me.
desperate. All right?

491
00:22:42.961 --> 00:22:46.296
He remembered a story
I told one night
at the table.

492
00:22:46.348 --> 00:22:47.843
The table?
Yeah. poker table.

493
00:22:47.867 --> 00:22:49.861
We're in one of
the floating games
around town.

494
00:22:49.885 --> 00:22:52.753
You know. small stakes.
right. but a good way
to blow off steam.

495
00:22:52.822 --> 00:22:56.289
But then
when he got laid off.
it stopped being a game.

496
00:22:56.358 --> 00:22:59.593
He started betting
to make up his paycheck.
but the stakes were too low.

497
00:22:59.662 --> 00:23:02.129
So he went to Chinatown.

498
00:23:03.315 --> 00:23:05.032
The mob-run games.

499
00:23:05.100 --> 00:23:09.186
Yeah. Triads. He did
fine for a bit. you know.
but luck's a fickle bitch.

500
00:23:09.255 --> 00:23:11.338
He lost more than he had
to the wrong guy.

501
00:23:11.406 --> 00:23:13.118
He couldn't make enough
to cover his losses.

502
00:23:13.142 --> 00:23:14.969
Yeah. that's when he
remembered the night
I told the story

503
00:23:14.993 --> 00:23:16.388
about my own fiscal emergency.

504
00:23:16.412 --> 00:23:20.331
about how I went to Mexico
and made 50 grand in one day.

505
00:23:20.399 --> 00:23:24.418
That's when I figured.
"Hey. what the hell.
Just pay it forward."

506
00:23:24.486 --> 00:23:25.881
All right.
this guy that he owed.

507
00:23:25.905 --> 00:23:27.849
Did he give you
a description?
A name?

508
00:23:27.873 --> 00:23:33.444
No name. John thought
he was Russian mafia
because of all his tattoos.

509
00:23:33.496 --> 00:23:35.340
RYAN: Some tatted-up
Russian mobster was
after me.

510
00:23:35.364 --> 00:23:37.225
I could see taking
a job as a drug mule.

511
00:23:37.249 --> 00:23:39.410
ESPOSITO:
A tattooed Russian
in New York City?

512
00:23:39.434 --> 00:23:40.968
Well. that narrows it down.

513
00:23:41.036 --> 00:23:43.482
We conduct an investigation
based on the information
we have.

514
00:23:43.506 --> 00:23:45.423
not the evidence we need.

515
00:23:45.491 --> 00:23:48.069
Well. Bigby says that
the Russian hangs out
at the club in Chinatown.

516
00:23:48.093 --> 00:23:49.905
Why don't we just go there?

517
00:23:49.929 --> 00:23:52.095
The games are
word-of-mouth. bro.

518
00:23:52.164 --> 00:23:53.742
They don't just share with cops.

519
00:23:53.766 --> 00:23:55.710
Well. luckily.
I'm not a cop.
Castle.

520
00:23:55.734 --> 00:23:57.117
What? It's perfect.

521
00:23:57.185 --> 00:23:59.948
I go in.
scope the place out
until I ID the Russian.

522
00:23:59.972 --> 00:24:02.822
Hey. you know.
that's not a bad plan.

523
00:24:02.891 --> 00:24:04.958
We still have to find the game.

524
00:24:05.027 --> 00:24:06.727
Leave that to me.

525
00:24:06.795 --> 00:24:08.373
It's a pretty good story. Ricky.

526
00:24:08.397 --> 00:24:10.876
Yeah. it's got
a big opening.
major twist.

527
00:24:10.900 --> 00:24:14.301
Though I gotta say.
I saw that whole
"drug mule" thing coming.

528
00:24:14.369 --> 00:24:17.354
Nice try. Connelly.
You're not gonna
goad me into raising.

529
00:24:17.423 --> 00:24:21.442
Stephen. you once wrote
about an underground
poker game in <i>King Con.</i>

530
00:24:21.510 --> 00:24:23.438
Yeah.
And you once
had Harry Bosch

531
00:24:23.462 --> 00:24:25.395
investigate the murder
of a poker player.

532
00:24:25.464 --> 00:24:27.131
Yeah. <i>One Dollar Jackpot.</i>
Why?

533
00:24:27.200 --> 00:24:29.900
Well. Michael.
this guy that
we're looking for.

534
00:24:29.968 --> 00:24:33.086
he's a regular in
the Triad-run games
in Chinatown.

535
00:24:33.172 --> 00:24:35.906
I thought maybe
one of you knew someone
who could get me in?

536
00:24:35.974 --> 00:24:39.487
What. are you nuts?
Those are crooks and
killers down there.

537
00:24:39.511 --> 00:24:41.740
Look. Ricky.
Doing the research
is one thing.

538
00:24:41.764 --> 00:24:43.730
but the Russian mafia?
The Triad?

539
00:24:43.799 --> 00:24:45.427
You tangle with those people.

540
00:24:45.451 --> 00:24:47.429
and all the best sellers
in the world are not gonna
protect you.

541
00:24:47.453 --> 00:24:48.880
I know. I know.
I don't plan on tangling.

542
00:24:48.904 --> 00:24:51.344
I'm just gonna be
another rich.
bored thrill-seeker

543
00:24:51.373 --> 00:24:54.341
looking to try
my luck down there.

544
00:24:54.410 --> 00:24:56.154
You must really like her.

545
00:24:56.178 --> 00:24:57.461
Who?

546
00:24:57.529 --> 00:25:00.064
That police detective
of yours. Look. Rick.

547
00:25:00.132 --> 00:25:03.834
There's only one reason
that you'd be dumb enough
to go down there.

548
00:25:03.903 --> 00:25:05.980
and that's to impress a girl.

549
00:25:06.004 --> 00:25:09.673
Why don't you cut yourself
a little slack and just buy
her some flowers?

550
00:25:09.742 --> 00:25:11.975
Do you know the place or not?

551
00:25:14.196 --> 00:25:15.362
Well?

552
00:25:25.090 --> 00:25:27.235
Are you sure this is the place?

553
00:25:27.259 --> 00:25:30.060
Cannell has never
steered me wrong.

554
00:25:30.129 --> 00:25:32.489
Okay. Button cam's
in place. Ryan?

555
00:25:32.547 --> 00:25:33.725
<i>In place. Ryan?</i>

556
00:25:33.749 --> 00:25:36.316
Good for picture and...
<i>picture and...</i>

557
00:25:36.384 --> 00:25:37.751
Sound.

558
00:25:37.820 --> 00:25:41.588
All right. So remember.
we can hear you.
but you can't hear us.

559
00:25:41.657 --> 00:25:44.875
So once you leave this van.
you're on your own. okay?

560
00:25:44.944 --> 00:25:47.304
All right. tell me
the plan again.

561
00:25:47.363 --> 00:25:49.629
I go in. I find
the tattooed Russian.

562
00:25:49.698 --> 00:25:51.643
I get a clear picture
of him. and I get
the hell out of there.

563
00:25:51.667 --> 00:25:54.012
And you don't
stay any longer
than you need to.

564
00:25:54.036 --> 00:25:56.036
I'll be fine.
Besides. it's Chinatown.

565
00:25:56.104 --> 00:25:59.005
How many Russian poker
players can there be?

566
00:26:11.403 --> 00:26:13.904
Anybody else have
a bad feeling about this?

567
00:26:13.972 --> 00:26:15.812
Yeah.
Yeah. that's what I thought.

568
00:27:17.586 --> 00:27:19.286
Go ahead and deal.

569
00:27:22.758 --> 00:27:24.424
One on the rocks.

570
00:27:32.651 --> 00:27:33.884
(WHISPERS) I'm in.

571
00:27:38.057 --> 00:27:39.789
Tattooed Russian.

572
00:27:42.962 --> 00:27:45.395
There's another
tattooed Russian.

573
00:27:48.934 --> 00:27:52.602
There's a whole table
of tattooed Russians.

574
00:27:55.340 --> 00:28:00.494
Apparently. there are
a lot more Russians in
Chinatown than I thought.

575
00:28:08.320 --> 00:28:11.187
So. the Russians
are regulars here.

576
00:28:11.256 --> 00:28:13.518
but only a handful of them
play at the no-limit table.

577
00:28:13.542 --> 00:28:15.809
which is where John Allen
would have gone.

578
00:28:15.878 --> 00:28:18.890
The guy said
they're card bullies.
pushing up pots.

579
00:28:18.914 --> 00:28:22.044
<i>forcing their opponents</i>
<i>to bet more just to stay</i>
<i>in the game.</i>

580
00:28:22.068 --> 00:28:24.579
RYAN: You think he has
any idea he's recapping
a conversation

581
00:28:24.603 --> 00:28:26.231
that we just heard
in its entirety?

582
00:28:26.255 --> 00:28:28.255
Give the guy a gadget.
he thinks he's Bond.

583
00:28:28.324 --> 00:28:29.935
Let's just hope
he remembers he's
wearing a camera

584
00:28:29.959 --> 00:28:31.335
before he goes and takes a leak.

585
00:28:31.359 --> 00:28:32.704
Why would you even...
Trust me.

586
00:28:32.728 --> 00:28:35.112
CASTLE: <i>what kind of
trouble I can stir up.</i>

587
00:28:35.181 --> 00:28:37.021
I'm going to go
sit at the table.

588
00:28:37.066 --> 00:28:39.166
see if I can find anything out.

589
00:28:41.287 --> 00:28:42.836
What did he say?

590
00:28:42.904 --> 00:28:44.382
He just said he's
taking a seat...
That's not the plan.

591
00:28:44.406 --> 00:28:46.590
That's not the plan. Castle!

592
00:28:48.810 --> 00:28:50.527
How's it going?

593
00:28:50.595 --> 00:28:52.328
This is no-limit table.

594
00:28:52.381 --> 00:28:56.383
Which is perfect.
because I am a no-limit
kind of guy.

595
00:28:56.452 --> 00:28:58.485
Change for 20.000. please.

596
00:29:01.156 --> 00:29:04.007
BECKETT: No. no.
no. no. no. no!
No! What's he doing?

597
00:29:04.076 --> 00:29:07.476
Dropping half
my yearly salary like
it was pocket change.

598
00:29:09.397 --> 00:29:10.763
Nice tats.

599
00:29:15.454 --> 00:29:20.156
Tat... No. tattoos.
The tat... It's nice.
What do they say?

600
00:29:20.209 --> 00:29:23.227
It says mind
your own business
and play cards.

601
00:29:23.295 --> 00:29:25.229
All right.
Don't mean to pry.

602
00:29:25.297 --> 00:29:27.497
I'm just...
I'm actually
just a writer.

603
00:29:27.533 --> 00:29:30.300
I'm just doing
a little bit of
research.

604
00:29:30.368 --> 00:29:32.302
RUSSIAN: <i>A writer. huh?</i>

605
00:29:32.371 --> 00:29:34.731
Anything we might have heard of?

606
00:29:36.007 --> 00:29:37.908
<i>Storm Fall. Storm's Last Stand.</i>

607
00:29:37.976 --> 00:29:39.509
Derrick Storm.
Yeah.

608
00:29:39.578 --> 00:29:42.962
I love this guy.
Why did you kill him?

609
00:29:43.032 --> 00:29:44.876
It's a long story.
But I'm working on
a new one

610
00:29:44.900 --> 00:29:46.567
about underground poker.

611
00:29:46.635 --> 00:29:48.201
<i>Very hush-hush.</i>

612
00:29:48.270 --> 00:29:50.832
<i>I just kind of came</i>
<i>down here to get a feel</i>
<i>for the world. you know?</i>

613
00:29:50.856 --> 00:29:53.334
And you.
you want for it
to be authentic.

614
00:29:53.358 --> 00:29:55.058
Exactly.

615
00:29:55.127 --> 00:29:56.993
No problem.

616
00:29:57.062 --> 00:29:58.896
(SPEAKING IN RUSSIAN)

617
00:30:07.656 --> 00:30:08.939
Yeah.

618
00:30:09.008 --> 00:30:10.451
RYAN: Seems like
he's making friends.

619
00:30:10.475 --> 00:30:12.837
They just said
they're gonna take him
for everything he's got.

620
00:30:12.861 --> 00:30:14.461
What. you speak Russian?

621
00:30:14.530 --> 00:30:17.931
Semester in Kiev
between junior
and senior year.

622
00:30:17.999 --> 00:30:21.100
Sometimes. when I am bored.
I go to Glechik Cafe
in Little Odessa

623
00:30:21.169 --> 00:30:23.519
and pretend to be Muscovite.

624
00:30:23.588 --> 00:30:25.538
Now. that's kind of hot.

625
00:30:27.559 --> 00:30:28.725
Raise.

626
00:30:30.695 --> 00:30:31.895
Call.

627
00:30:33.031 --> 00:30:34.281
I call.

628
00:30:45.427 --> 00:30:47.105
Check the players' hands.
See if there's anything

629
00:30:47.129 --> 00:30:49.929
that'll explain
the bruise patterns
on our vic's neck.

630
00:30:53.435 --> 00:30:54.551
Call.

631
00:30:55.887 --> 00:31:00.457
Mr. Castle. tell me
a little bit more
about this book.

632
00:31:00.525 --> 00:31:04.444
Well. it's about
a Russian mobster
with a taste for cards.

633
00:31:05.530 --> 00:31:08.915
He preys off of desperation.

634
00:31:08.984 --> 00:31:12.102
luring people into betting
more than they have.

635
00:31:17.643 --> 00:31:20.510
And why would he do this?

636
00:31:20.579 --> 00:31:22.862
Because he's also a loan shark.

637
00:31:24.699 --> 00:31:26.578
<i>See. he fronts his victims
and makes bank on the vig.</i>

638
00:31:26.602 --> 00:31:27.678
What the hell's he doing?

639
00:31:27.702 --> 00:31:29.336
He's playing poker.

640
00:31:29.404 --> 00:31:31.366
He's trying to provoke
one of these guys into
giving up their hand.

641
00:31:31.390 --> 00:31:32.917
Or he's trying to
tip off our killer.

642
00:31:32.941 --> 00:31:34.018
CASTLE: <i>But this one guy.</i>

643
00:31:34.042 --> 00:31:37.677
a family guy. he gets
in a little too deep.

644
00:31:37.746 --> 00:31:39.863
He can't pay the loan back.

645
00:31:39.932 --> 00:31:43.533
So the mobster got no choice.

646
00:31:43.602 --> 00:31:48.221
Has to kill him.
send a message to
anyone else who owes him.

647
00:31:48.290 --> 00:31:53.527
So one night. he lures him
into an abandoned building.

648
00:31:53.595 --> 00:31:56.863
strangles him to death
and throws him off the roof.

649
00:31:58.951 --> 00:32:00.450
Sounds like lot of work.

650
00:32:00.518 --> 00:32:02.697
Why not just put
bullet in his head?

651
00:32:02.721 --> 00:32:04.471
<i>Much more simple.</i>

652
00:32:04.540 --> 00:32:06.420
Bang.
Oh. my God.

653
00:32:09.995 --> 00:32:11.528
Hey. Ryan. check this out.

654
00:32:11.597 --> 00:32:12.857
What is he doing
with his finger?

655
00:32:12.881 --> 00:32:14.514
BECKETT:
Punch in on that.

656
00:32:16.852 --> 00:32:18.602
It's a prosthetic.

657
00:32:18.670 --> 00:32:21.738
That's why it didn't
leave a mark on our vic.
That's our guy.

658
00:32:21.806 --> 00:32:23.000
Hey. if he thinks
Castle's a threat.

659
00:32:23.024 --> 00:32:24.752
he's...
We gotta get him
out of there. now.

660
00:32:24.776 --> 00:32:25.987
Their security's
pretty well-armed.

661
00:32:26.011 --> 00:32:27.338
We go in as cops.
it might get messy.

662
00:32:27.362 --> 00:32:28.461
What are you doing?

663
00:32:28.530 --> 00:32:30.229
I'm gonna go in there.

664
00:32:30.298 --> 00:32:31.776
And if I'm
not out in 10 minutes.
you guys call for backup.

665
00:32:31.800 --> 00:32:34.334
Can I have my purse. please?

666
00:32:34.403 --> 00:32:36.336
What're you gonna do?
Lip gloss them to death?

667
00:32:36.404 --> 00:32:38.171
Something like that.

668
00:33:33.012 --> 00:33:37.080
Come on. boys.
My boyfriend is waiting.

669
00:33:37.149 --> 00:33:40.466
He is player.
If I don't go inside.
he will lose.

670
00:33:40.535 --> 00:33:44.621
I'm his lucky charm.
you know? No?

671
00:33:46.025 --> 00:33:50.327
Well. maybe I can be
a lucky charm for you.

672
00:33:50.396 --> 00:33:53.563
We win. and when I'm
in there we always win.

673
00:33:53.632 --> 00:33:58.001
and then maybe I can share
some of my boyfriend's luck
with you.

674
00:34:03.959 --> 00:34:05.258
All in.

675
00:34:08.129 --> 00:34:11.849
It's a big pot.
Mr. Writer Man.
All that money.

676
00:34:12.684 --> 00:34:14.829
But then what is money
to a millionaire. huh?

677
00:34:14.853 --> 00:34:18.872
You just can write
it off on your taxes
as doing research.

678
00:34:21.426 --> 00:34:22.859
CASTLE: All in.

679
00:34:24.796 --> 00:34:30.016
(CHUCKLING)
You are like character
in your book. in too deep.

680
00:34:32.354 --> 00:34:33.903
Three queens.

681
00:34:36.591 --> 00:34:38.558
That's very impressive.

682
00:34:40.746 --> 00:34:44.030
Not a lot can beat three queens.

683
00:34:44.099 --> 00:34:47.133
Except an inside straight.
maybe. Sweetheart. this is
for you.

684
00:34:47.202 --> 00:34:50.169
Would you change this
into something a little
smaller that I can carry?

685
00:34:50.238 --> 00:34:52.238
Now that is a big pile of money.

686
00:34:52.307 --> 00:34:54.508
But what's money
to a mobster. right?

687
00:35:01.883 --> 00:35:02.982
Walk.

688
00:35:05.337 --> 00:35:07.398
Who are you?
I told you.
I'm. I'm a novelist.

689
00:35:07.422 --> 00:35:09.784
The story.
The dead man. the roof.
Who told you? Who knows?

690
00:35:09.808 --> 00:35:11.252
His family knows.
His children know.

691
00:35:11.276 --> 00:35:13.410
If he paid what he owed.
he'd be home with them now.

692
00:35:13.478 --> 00:35:15.978
But he crossed me.
And now you have
crossed me.

693
00:35:16.047 --> 00:35:17.592
No. no. no. no.
I'm just a writer.

694
00:35:17.616 --> 00:35:20.283
Do not lie!
You are cop.

695
00:35:20.352 --> 00:35:25.605
Him. a cop?
Don't make me laugh.
He's barely even a man.

696
00:35:26.224 --> 00:35:27.239
Beckett?

697
00:35:27.308 --> 00:35:29.158
But you are a man. aren't you?

698
00:35:29.227 --> 00:35:31.494
A very handsome man.

699
00:35:31.562 --> 00:35:34.681
Richard. are you bothering
this handsome man?

700
00:35:34.749 --> 00:35:37.450
Go away.

701
00:35:37.518 --> 00:35:40.520
Okay. Boys and their guns.
Am I supposed to be
impressed?

702
00:35:40.589 --> 00:35:42.054
It doesn't concern you.

703
00:35:42.141 --> 00:35:43.572
Actually...

704
00:35:44.726 --> 00:35:46.025
It does.

705
00:35:47.562 --> 00:35:49.963
Is it just my imagination
or did you change?

706
00:35:50.032 --> 00:35:52.343
Castle. could you get
some backup. please?

707
00:35:52.367 --> 00:35:54.600
Yeah. Yeah.
Quiet.

708
00:35:54.669 --> 00:35:56.036
Thank you.

709
00:36:00.125 --> 00:36:01.391
This way.

710
00:36:13.472 --> 00:36:15.004
So. how is she?

711
00:36:17.192 --> 00:36:22.028
It's hard when everything
you thought you knew
turns out to be a lie.

712
00:36:22.097 --> 00:36:25.598
Well. not everything
was a lie. Not her
husband's love.

713
00:36:25.667 --> 00:36:29.586
I mean. sometimes we do
the wrong things for
the right reasons.

714
00:36:32.590 --> 00:36:36.459
So our case is closed.
I guess your <i>Cosmo</i> story
gets a happy ending.

715
00:36:36.527 --> 00:36:41.297
Speaking of happy endings.
thanks for saving my life.

716
00:36:41.366 --> 00:36:44.150
I was just trying
to avoid paperwork.

717
00:36:44.218 --> 00:36:46.152
We make a pretty good team.
you know.

718
00:36:46.220 --> 00:36:47.670
Like Starsky and Hutch.

719
00:36:47.739 --> 00:36:51.791
Tango and Cash.
Turner and Hooch.

720
00:36:51.860 --> 00:36:54.538
You know. now that
you mention it. you do
remind me a little of Hooch.

721
00:36:54.562 --> 00:36:55.662
Mmm.

722
00:36:59.684 --> 00:37:02.668
It's because
you're afraid.
isn't it?

723
00:37:02.737 --> 00:37:05.238
You're afraid that
if you look into
your mother's death.

724
00:37:05.307 --> 00:37:09.175
that you'll go back
down that rabbit hole
and lose yourself again.

725
00:37:09.243 --> 00:37:11.611
But it's different this time.

726
00:37:13.014 --> 00:37:17.233
We have good leads.
We have strong leads.

727
00:37:17.302 --> 00:37:22.221
And you won't
have to do it alone.
We can do it together.

728
00:37:24.309 --> 00:37:27.911
What if I don't wanna know?
Did you ever think of that?

729
00:37:31.366 --> 00:37:32.865
What if I'm not ready?

730
00:37:32.934 --> 00:37:34.945
What if the idea
of catching
my mom's murderer

731
00:37:34.969 --> 00:37:37.415
and then having to
sit there and watch
as he cuts some deal

732
00:37:37.439 --> 00:37:39.650
that puts him back
out on the street
in 10 years

733
00:37:39.674 --> 00:37:41.824
makes me nauseous?

734
00:37:41.893 --> 00:37:44.444
You dredged up my past
for you. Castle.

735
00:37:44.513 --> 00:37:47.780
not for me.
and you're too selfish
to even see it.

736
00:37:50.168 --> 00:37:53.152
The case is closed. Castle.

737
00:37:53.221 --> 00:37:56.741
We made a deal.
and I expect you
to honor it.

738
00:38:33.945 --> 00:38:35.495
You're writing?

739
00:38:35.564 --> 00:38:36.929
It's time.

740
00:38:40.568 --> 00:38:42.018
And Beckett?

741
00:38:45.791 --> 00:38:47.390
I'm sorry. Dad.

742
00:38:48.409 --> 00:38:50.810
So how was the movie?

743
00:38:50.879 --> 00:38:52.244
We didn't go.

744
00:38:52.313 --> 00:38:53.530
Why not?

745
00:38:53.598 --> 00:38:54.714
Owen.

746
00:38:56.250 --> 00:38:57.483
What happened?

747
00:38:57.552 --> 00:38:59.430
He was playing video games
and lost track of time.

748
00:38:59.454 --> 00:39:02.254
By the time he showed up.
it was too late.

749
00:39:05.744 --> 00:39:07.377
Sorry. sweetie.

750
00:39:07.446 --> 00:39:10.007
And then when he did
show up. he tried to act
like it's no big deal.

751
00:39:10.031 --> 00:39:11.681
Like I'm overreacting.

752
00:39:11.750 --> 00:39:13.316
I mean. he didn't even call.

753
00:39:15.353 --> 00:39:17.787
Why do boys do that?

754
00:39:17.855 --> 00:39:20.423
Why do they always have
to justify everything?

755
00:39:22.360 --> 00:39:24.977
Why can't they just
say they're sorry?

756
00:39:35.374 --> 00:39:36.689
Thank you.

757
00:39:37.592 --> 00:39:38.841
For what?

758
00:39:38.910 --> 00:39:41.578
For just being you.

759
00:40:05.036 --> 00:40:08.671
I'm sorry.
What I did was wrong.

760
00:40:10.058 --> 00:40:11.690
I violated your trust.

761
00:40:11.759 --> 00:40:15.427
I opened old wounds.
and I did not respect
your wishes.

762
00:40:17.866 --> 00:40:19.343
And if we're not gonna
see each other again.

763
00:40:19.367 --> 00:40:21.467
then you deserve to know...

764
00:40:23.237 --> 00:40:25.705
I'm very. very sorry.

765
00:40:39.187 --> 00:40:40.427
BECKETT: Castle.

766
00:40:44.575 --> 00:40:46.408
I'll see you tomorrow.
